## Architecture Rules
- Server Components by default. Only interactive elements (forms, modals, filters) become Client Components.
- No state management library. React Server Components + URL search params + form actions.
- Supabase Auth with middleware for session checking.
- All images compressed client-side before upload (max 1200px, WebP).
- RLS policies on every table from day one.

## File Structure
```
src/
├── app/
│   ├── (auth)/          ← login, public pages
│   ├── (dashboard)/     ← protected app pages
│   └── api/             ← webhooks, external APIs
├── components/
│   ├── ui/              ← shadcn/ui base components
│   └── [module]/        ← module-specific components
├── lib/
│   ├── supabase/        ← client, server, admin clients
│   ├── types.ts         ← TypeScript types from schema
│   └── utils.ts         ← shared utilities
└── hooks/               ← custom React hooks
```

## Conventions
- Use Zod for all form validation
- Server actions for mutations (not API routes)
- Toast notifications for success/error feedback
- Auto-refresh data after mutations
- signOut must use `{ scope: 'local' }` to prevent global session revocation

## What NOT to Do
- Do NOT add state management libraries (Redux, Zustand, etc.)
- Do NOT create API routes for CRUD — use server actions
- Do NOT use `use client` on page components — only on interactive children
- Do NOT store secrets in code — use environment variables
- Do NOT skip RLS policies — even for admin-only MVP

